The food isn’t as cheap as one may think – local fruits and vegetables are cheaper, for example, while imported ones are more expensive

PROS of living in Cyprus:

It’s affordable – renting or owning property is much cheaper than in Western Europe (especially Germany), and the population is considered to be numerous enough (1,0 million) for work opportunities to be abundant in a considerable number of sectors

The climate – Cyprus combines the good in other areas around the world. No winter snow, no extreme summer heat, plenty of sunshine and a beautiful sea for swimming and sailing in all the right seasons

The people are kind – it’s very rare that one will face an attitude problem from local Cypriots when one has a (correct) question or a problem to resolve

The weather is a gem – once one has found out what clothes to pack, what not to pack and how to manage work, home life, and the weather is all well and good

The Greek tradition is very present – thanks to the Greeks’ love for balmy evenings outdoors; eating, drinking, playing cards, dominoes… the penis, is the most common symbol to be found on the Cypriot hospital grounds, a hilly, tree-lined mountain on the north-eastern tip of Paralimni is the Archangelos Michael and St. George.
